body: <a href="#"><img alt="P0" src="https://greptile-static-assets.s3.amazonaws.com/badges/p0.svg?v=7" align="top"></a> **Unvalidated `proxy_ep` bypasses SSRF protection**

The `proxy_ep` hostname is taken directly from the Copilot token exchange response and embedded into `format!("https://{ep}")` without any validation. This bypasses the project's SSRF protection layer (which blocks loopback, private/RFC-1918, link-local, and CGNAT ranges). A compromised token exchange response or an attacker-controlled value could supply `proxy_ep` as `169.254.169.254` (cloud metadata endpoint), `192.168.1.1`, or `evil.com@internal.host` to redirect all API calls to internal infrastructure.

The CLAUDE.md security notes explicitly state: _"SSRF protection: `web_fetch.rs` blocks loopback/private/link-local/CGNAT IPs. Preserve this on changes."_ The proxy endpoint introduced here sidesteps that protection entirely.

At minimum, validate that `ep` contains only safe hostname characters before constructing the URL:

```rust
Some(ep) => {
    let ep = ep.trim();
    // Reject anything that isn't a plain hostname (no slashes, @, colons, etc.)
    if !ep.chars().all(|c| c.is_ascii_alphanumeric() || matches!(c, '.' | '-')) {
        warn!(proxy_ep = %ep, "ignoring malformed proxy-ep, falling back to individual endpoint");
        return CopilotAuth { token, base_url: COPILOT_API_BASE.to_string(), is_enterprise: false };
    }
    debug!(proxy_ep = %ep, "using enterprise proxy endpoint");
    CopilotAuth {
        token,
        base_url: format!("https://{ep}"),
        is_enterprise: true,
    }
}
```

