The allowlist — ASCII alphanumeric, `.`, and `-` — only blocks URL injection tricks (slashes, `@`-redirects, whitespace). It does **not** block plain IPv4 addresses: `169.254.169.254` (cloud IMDS), `127.0.0.1`, `192.168.1.1`, and `10.0.0.1` all consist solely of digits and dots and pass `all(|c| c.is_ascii_alphanumeric() || matches!(c, '.' | '-'))`.

CLAUDE.md's security section explicitly requires preserving SSRF protection (`web_fetch.rs` blocks loopback/private/link-local/CGNAT IPs). A compromised token exchange response supplying `proxy-ep: 169.254.169.254` would route every API call to the cloud metadata endpoint.

Add a second guard that rejects values that parse as an IP address:

```suggestion
        Some(ep) => {
            let ep = ep.trim();
            // Reject anything that isn't a plain hostname (no slashes, @-redirects, etc.)
            if !ep
                .chars()
                .all(|c| c.is_ascii_alphanumeric() || matches!(c, '.' | '-'))
            {
                warn!(proxy_ep = %ep, "ignoring malformed proxy-ep, falling back to individual endpoint");
                return CopilotAuth {
                    token,
                    base_url: COPILOT_API_BASE.to_string(),
                    is_enterprise: false,
                };
            }
            // Additionally reject bare IP addresses (v4 or v6) to prevent
            // SSRF against cloud metadata services, loopback, and RFC-1918 ranges.
            if ep.parse::<std::net::IpAddr>().is_ok() {
                warn!(proxy_ep = %ep, "ignoring IP-address proxy-ep, falling back to individual endpoint");
                return CopilotAuth {
                    token,
                    base_url: COPILOT_API_BASE.to_string(),
                    is_enterprise: false,
                };
            }
```

